\begin_layout Section
Investor Preferences and Utility Functions 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: investorPreferencesConcaveUtilityFncs"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The question of how to choose among investment opportunities (or, more generally
, among uncertain prospects) has a rich history, with interdisciplinary
 contributions by gamblers, economists, mathematicians and psychologists
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Mathematicians and gamblers worked more closely than one might imagine –
 mathematicians often derived results and sold them to gamblers for immediate
 use in the field!
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Early on, it was broadly accepted that the fair price of entry to a game
 of chance was the expected value of its payoff.
 By way of example, if the flip of a coin returned $0 or $2 with equal probabili
ty, the fair price for participation in this game was held to be 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5\cdot\$0+0.5\cdot\$2=\$1$
\end_inset

.
 But in 1710, Nicolaus Bernoulli described a simple game, now known as the
 St.
 Petersburg game, that threw this belief into doubt.
 The St.
 Petersburg game is played as follows: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A fair coin is repeatedly flipped, and the number of flips till the first
 appearance of a head, which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, is noted.
 The gambler is then paid 
\begin_inset Formula $\$2^{k}$
\end_inset

 for participating in the game.
 As the probability of first seeing a head on the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 flip is 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{1}{2^{k}}$
\end_inset

, the expected payoff from this game is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\left[\mathrm{Payoff}\right] & =\sum_{k\,\geqslant\,1}\frac{1}{2^{k}}\cdot\$2^{k}\nonumber \\
 & =\infty.\label{eq:StPetersburgPayoff}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But no gambler would pay an infinite amount to participate in this game.
 In practice, gamblers seem to be willing to pay no more than about $20
 for the privilege of participating in the St.
 Petersburg game, a paradox if there ever was one! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nicolas Bernoulli's cousin Daniel
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Bernoullis were a remarkable family, as well known for their contributions
 to mathematics as for their feuds.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 attempted to resolve the paradox by positing that the pleaure (or 
\emph on
utility
\emph default
) associated with a $1 increase in wealth would be the reciprocal of the
 initial level of wealth, and that gamblers could therefore be expected
 to have logarithmic utility for wealth
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As we shall see, these two views are mathematically equivalent.
 In modern language, Daniel Bernoulli asserted that the marginal utility
 of wealth was the reciprocal of wealth.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The expected utility from participating in the St.
 Petersburg game is therefore
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\left[\ln\left(\mathrm{Payoff}\right)\right] & =\sum_{k\,\geqslant\,1}\frac{1}{2^{k}}\cdot\ln\left(2^{k}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{k\,\geqslant\,1}\frac{k}{2^{k}}\cdot\ln\left(2\right)\nonumber \\
 & =2\ln\left(2\right),\label{eq:StPetersburgUtility}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is finite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Moscati2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 traces the evolution of resolutions to this paradox, and also exposes the
 vigorous debates between competing schools of thought that finally settled
 down in the decade following the publication of an axiomatic theory of
 utility by John von Neumann and Oskar Morgenstern (VNM) in 1947.
 The VNM axioms are expressed in terms of preferences over random outcomes
 (or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lotteries
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $X\succ Y$
\end_inset

 to express a strong preference for lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 over lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim Y$
\end_inset

 to express indifference between the two lotteries.
 Likewise, we write 
\begin_inset Formula $X\succeq Y$
\end_inset

 to express a weak preference for lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 over lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X\succeq Y\equiv X\succ Y\ \mathrm{or}\ X\sim Y.\label{eq:XWeaklyPreferredToY}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\series bold
Axiom 1 (Completeness)
\series default
: All lotteries can be ranked.
 For any pair of lotteries 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, either 
\begin_inset Formula $X\succ Y$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\succ X$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim Y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\series bold
Axiom 2 (Transitivity)
\series default
: For any three lotteries 
\begin_inset Formula $X,\ Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X\succeq Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\succeq Z$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $X\succeq Z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\series bold
Axiom 3 (Substitution)
\series default
: For any three lotteries 
\begin_inset Formula $X,\ Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X\succeq Y\succeq Z$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\sim p\,X+(1-p)\,Z$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p\,X+(1-p)\,Z$
\end_inset

 is interpreted as participation in lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and participation in lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "VonNeumann1947"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proved that if investors' preferences satisfied these three axioms, they
 would choose among risky alternatives so as to maximize their expected
 utility, and in spite of many fits, starts, and paradoxes, 
\emph on
Expected Utility Maximization
\emph default
 (EUM) has come to be the dominant paradigm for modeling choice in economics
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Some authors use a more fine-grained set of axioms, see for example the
 discussions of utility theory in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Levy2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Broadly speaking, the theoretical underpinnings of EUM rest on two key assumptio
ns:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
P1: Non-satiation: Investors prefer more wealth to less, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
P2: Risk aversion: Investors prefer less uncertainty to more.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
EUM requires investors to express their preferences via a 
\emph on
cardinal utility function
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cardinal utility assign a real number to each outcome of interest.
 Ordinal utility, in contrast, only specifies if one outcome is preferred
 to another.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})$
\end_inset

 that is a dimensionless function of investment end–of–period wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{\mathrm{v}}$
\end_inset

, and which is invariant under an affine transformation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{U}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})=a+b\cdot\mathit{U}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}}),\ b>0$
\end_inset

, in the sense that 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})$
\end_inset

 provide the same ranking among investment alternatives.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose an investor's preferences can be captured by such a utility function,
 whose values are sometimes referred to as 
\emph on
utils
\emph default
, and she chooses an investment that maximizes expected end–of–period utility
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[U(\mathrm{V})\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The form of the utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 will depend on the assumptions one makes about her preferences, and we
 next determine the implications of two simple and reasonable assumptions
 concerning investor preferences for utility functions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
P1: 
\series bold
Non-satiation
\series default
: At any level of wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

, the investor prefers a strictly larger wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}_{2}>\mathrm{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
P2: 
\series bold
Risk Aversion
\series default
: The investor maximizes her expected utility, and is
\emph on
 risk averse
\emph default
 in the following sense: she always prefers a fixed end of period wealth,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

, to a 
\emph on
fair game
\emph default
 in which end of period wealth is the random amount 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}=\mathrm{v}_{0}+\text{H}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is one of those occasions where it is useful to represent a random
 variable with a capital letter to distinguish it from an variable that
 is non–random (such as a particular realization) and so represented by
 a lower case letter.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}$
\end_inset

 has mean zero and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note in passing that investors are said to 
\emph on
weakly risk averse 
\emph default
if they are indifferent to participating in such a fair game.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Much of the utility theory literature uses the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

strictly risk averse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 where we use 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

risk averse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and uses 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

risk averse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 where we use 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weakly risk averse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These assumptions are not all–encompassing – the near–universal existence
 of casinos and lotteries indicates that there is no shortage of individuals
 who prefer (or sadly, are addicted to) the expected losses and uncertain
 outcomes that are endemic to gambling.
 Even more interesting, risk–averse and risk–seeking behavior can co-exist
 in the same individual: a great many people buy both life insurance and
 lottery tickets!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An investor with preferences P1 and P2 will use a utility function with
 the following properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
U1.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{\mathrm{v}}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
U2.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})$
\end_inset

 is strictly concave
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A 
\emph on
strictly concave
\emph default
 function is one for which a straight line connecting two distinct points
 on the 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})$
\end_inset

 curve lies strictly below the curve, except at the two end-points where
 the line joins the curve, as in the left–hand plot in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: ShapesOfUtilityFunctions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The mathematical definitions of concave and concave functions are given
 in Appendix A.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The utility property U1 follows immediately from P1.
 The concavity property U2 follows from P2 and Jensen's inequality
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See the discussion of convex and concave functions, as well as of Jensen's
 inequality, in Appendix A
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Plots/concave utility risk prefs.png
	lyxscale 20
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Shapes of Utility Functions
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: ShapesOfUtilityFunctions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The commonly occurring utility functions described in the next subsection
 have both first and second derivatives, and for such utility functions
 the properties U1 and U2 are equivalent to the following derivative properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
U1E: 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{\prime}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})>0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
U2E: 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{\prime\prime}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})<0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is known as its 
\emph on
marginal utility
\emph default
, and represents the increase in utility obtained from an additional dollar
 of wealth.
 While a
\emph on
 
\emph default
risk averse EUM investor is one whose differentiable utility function is
 concave, a 
\emph on
risk seeking
\emph default
 EUM investor is one whose utility function is strictly convex
\emph on

\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A 
\emph on
strictly convex
\emph default
 utility function is one that satisfies the U2E property with the inequality
 sign reversed.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.

\emph default
 An investor with a utility function that has a constant first derivative,
 and hence a zero second derivative, is said to be 
\emph on
risk neutral
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Concave Utility Functions and Risk Aversion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With property P2 in mind, consider the fair investment game with end-of-period
 wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}=\mathrm{v}_{0}+\mathrm{H}$
\end_inset

, where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{H}=\left\{ \begin{array}{cl}
\,\,\,\mathrm{h}_{1}:\ -\mathrm{v}_{0}<\mathrm{h}_{1}<0, & \mbox{with probability \ensuremath{p}}\\
\mathrm{h}_{2}:\ 0<\mathrm{h}_{2},\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \, & \mbox{with probability \ensuremath{1-p}}
\end{array}\right.\label{eq: fairGame}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with any fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{h}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{h}_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{H}\right]=p\,\mathrm{h}_{1}+(1-p)\,\mathrm{h}_{2}=0,\label{eq:E_H_eq_0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]=\mathrm{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this fair game, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{E}\left[U\left(\mathrm{V}\right)\right]=p\cdot U\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}+\mathrm{h}_{1}\right)+\left(1-p\right)\cdot U\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}+\mathrm{h}_{2}\right),\label{eq:E_U_of_V}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and since 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\mathrm{v}_{0})=\mathrm{E}\left[U(\mathrm{v}_{0})\right]$
\end_inset

, we also have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{E}\left[U(\mathrm{v}_{0})\right]=U\left(p\cdot\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}+\mathrm{h}_{1}\right)+\left(1-p\right)\cdot\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}+\mathrm{h}_{2}\right)\right).\label{eq:E_U_of_V_0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since by P2 our EUM investor is risk averse, she prefers the sure outcome
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

 to the risky outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

, and as she is also an expected utility maximizer, it must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[U(\mathrm{v}_{0})\right]>\mathrm{E}\left[U(\mathrm{V})\right]$
\end_inset

, and accordingly we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U\left(p\cdot\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}+\mathrm{h}_{1}\right)+\left(1-p\right)\cdot\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}+\mathrm{h}_{2}\right)\right)>p\cdot U\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}+\mathrm{h}_{1}\right)+\left(1-p\right)\cdot U\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}+\mathrm{h}_{2}\right)\label{eq:E_U_V_0_gt_U_E_V_0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all combinations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}_{0},\ -\mathrm{v}_{0}<\mathrm{h}_{1}<0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\mathrm{h}_{2}$
\end_inset

 that satisfy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:E_H_eq_0"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which is the same as asserting that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U\left(p\cdot\mathrm{v}_{1}+(1-p)\cdot\mathrm{v}_{2}\right)>p\cdot U\left(\mathrm{v}_{1}\right)+(1-p)\cdot U\left(\mathrm{v}_{2}\right),\ \forall\,\mathrm{v_{1}}<\mathrm{v}_{2}.\label{eq: strictConcavityCondition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But the above inequality is equivalent to the statement that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a strictly concave function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Certainty Equivalent Value and the Risk Premium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Sometimes portfolio managers want to compare portfolios that have different
 expected utilities in terms of monetary units rather the dimensionless
 units of utility functions.
 One way in which to do so is to define a dollar amount, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{\mathrm{v}}_{c}$
\end_inset

, known as the 
\emph on
Certainty Equivalent Value
\emph default
, that satisfies the equation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U(\mathit{\mathrm{v}}_{c}) & =\mathrm{E}[U(\mathrm{V})]\nonumber \\
 & \implies\mathit{\mathrm{v}}_{c}=U^{-1}\left(\mathrm{E}[U(\mathrm{V})]\right).\label{eq: certaintyEquivalent}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{\mathrm{v}}_{c}$
\end_inset

 as the lower, sure, value that a risk–averse investor would accept in place
 of the risky payoff 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

, with higher expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]$
\end_inset

, in order to avoid the uncertainty associated with the random character
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: certaintyEquivValue"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows graphically how such a value is obtained for a risk–averse investor
 when end–of–period random wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

 has expected utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[U(\mathrm{V})\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{\mathrm{v}}_{c}$
\end_inset

 is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]$
\end_inset

, in accordance with Jensen's equality for a (strictly) concave function,
 which asserts that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[U(\mathrm{V})\right]<U\left(\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]\right)$
\end_inset

 (see Appendix A).
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(\mathrm{v}_{c})=\mathrm{E}\left[U(\mathrm{V})\right]<U\left(\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and since 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}_{c}<\mathrm{E}[\mathrm{V}]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Plots/certaintyEquivalent.png
	lyxscale 20
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Certainty Equivalent Value for Expected Utility
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig: certaintyEquivValue"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The interpretation of a certainty equivalent value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{\mathrm{v}}_{c}$
\end_inset

 is that a risk–averse investor would give up a higher expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left[\mathrm{V}\right]$
\end_inset

 of terminal value of wealth for the smaller, sure, value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{\mathrm{v}}_{c}$
\end_inset

 in order to avoid the risk associated with the random character of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Correspondingly, the 
\emph on
Absolute Risk Premium
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{A}\left(\mathrm{v}\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{A}\left(\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]\right)=\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]-\mathit{\mathrm{v}}_{c},\label{eq:AbsoluteRiskPremium}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and this can be interpreted as the amount of wealth the investor is willing
 to forego (or the insurance premium she is willing to pay) to avoid the
 risk of a fair investment game.
 It can also be interpreted as the payment she would require in order to
 induce her to participate in a fair game.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Closely related to the Absolute Risk Premium is the 
\emph on
Relative Risk Premium
\emph default
, or the fraction of her wealth that a risk averse investor would pay to
 avoid the risk of a fair investment game (or would have to be paid in order
 to induce her to participate in a fair investment game):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\pi_{R}\left(\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]\right) & =\frac{\pi_{A}\left(\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]\right)}{\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]-\mathit{\mathrm{v}}_{c}}{\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]}.\label{eq:RelativeRiskPremium}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Absolute and Relative Risk Aversion
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: derivationOfRiskAversionFncs"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The risk premium is a function both of how uncertain an investment is and
 the shape of the investor's utility curve, and we so separate the contributions
 of these two influences.
 Once again, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

 be an initial level of wealth, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}=\mathrm{v}_{0}+\mathrm{H}$
\end_inset

 with random payoff 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}$
\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 be the
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 end-of-period random wealth
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U({\rm V})$
\end_inset

 be the investor's utility function.
 Suppose further that the investment is a fair game with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{H}\right]=0$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{{\rm V}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 be the variance of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm H}.$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}_{c}$
\end_inset

 be the certainty equivalent for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[{\rm V}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{A}\left(\mathrm{V}\right)$
\end_inset

 be the associated absolute risk premium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we expand 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\mathrm{V})$
\end_inset

 in a two–term Taylor series around its mean, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U(\mathrm{V}) & \thickapprox U(\mathrm{\mathit{\mathrm{E}}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]})\,+\,U^{\prime}(\mathrm{\mathit{\mathrm{E}}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]})\left(\mathrm{V}-\mathrm{\mathit{\mathrm{E}}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]}\right)\,+\,\frac{1}{2}\cdot U^{\prime\prime}(\mathrm{V})\left(\mathrm{V}-\mathrm{\mathit{\mathrm{E}}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]}\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =U(\mathrm{v}_{0})\,+\,U^{\prime}(\mathrm{\mathrm{v}_{0}})\left(\mathrm{V}-\mathrm{\mathrm{v}_{0}}\right)\,+\,\frac{1}{2}\cdot U^{\prime\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})\left(\mathrm{V}-\mathrm{\mathrm{v}_{0}}\right)^{2}\label{eq:UtilityTaylorSeries1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the second line follows from the observation that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]=\mathrm{v}_{0}+\mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{H}\right]=\mathrm{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Likewise, we can perform a one-term Taylor series expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\mathrm{V})$
\end_inset

 around its mean and write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U(\mathrm{\mathit{\mathrm{v}}_{c}}) & \thickapprox U(\mathrm{\mathit{\mathrm{E}}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]})\,+\,U^{\prime}(\mathrm{\mathit{\mathrm{E}}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]})\left(\mathrm{\mathit{\mathrm{v}}_{c}}-\mathrm{\mathit{\mathrm{E}}\left[\mathrm{V}\right]}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =U(\mathrm{v}_{0})\,+\,U^{\prime}(\mathrm{\mathrm{v}_{0}})\left(\mathrm{\mathit{\mathrm{v}}_{c}}-\mathrm{\mathrm{v}_{0}}\right).\label{eq:UtilityTaylorSeries2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On taking the expectation of both sides of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:UtilityTaylorSeries1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we see that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{E}\left[U(\mathrm{V})\right] & \triangleq U(\mathrm{v}_{c})\nonumber \\
 & \thickapprox U(\mathrm{v}_{0})\,+\,\frac{1}{2}\cdot U^{\prime\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})\cdot\sigma_{H}^{2}\label{eq:UtilityTaylorSeries3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:UtilityTaylorSeries2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:UtilityTaylorSeries3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and simplifying, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{\mathit{\mathrm{v}}_{0}}-\mathrm{\mathrm{v}_{c}} & \triangleq\pi_{A}\left(\mathrm{\mathit{\mathrm{v}}_{0}}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =-\frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{U^{\prime\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})}{U^{\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})}\cdot\sigma_{H}^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\cdot\mathrm{\mathit{ARA}(\mathrm{v}_{0})}\cdot\sigma_{H}^{2},\label{eq:UtilityTaylorSeries5}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where Absolute Risk Aversion is defined to be 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathit{ARA}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})}=-\frac{\mathrm{\mathit{U}''(\mathrm{v})}}{\mathrm{\mathit{U}'(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})}}.\label{eq: ARAfunction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can derive a similar expression for Relative Risk Aversion starting with
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RelativeRiskPremium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\pi_{R}\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}\right) & =\frac{\pi_{A}\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}\right)}{\mathrm{v}_{0}}\nonumber \\
 & =-\frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{U^{\prime\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})}{U^{\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})}\cdot\frac{\mathrm{v}_{0}}{\mathrm{v}_{0}^{2}}\cdot\sigma_{H}^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =-\frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{U^{\prime\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})\cdot\mathrm{v}_{0}}{U^{\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})}\cdot\sigma_{\nicefrac{H}{\mathrm{v}_{0}}}^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\cdot\mathrm{\mathit{RRA}(\mathrm{v}_{0})\cdot\sigma_{\nicefrac{H}{\mathrm{v}_{0}}}^{2}}\label{eq:UtilityTaylorSeries6}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where Relative Risk Aversion (RRA) is defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{\mathit{RRA}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})} & =\mathrm{v}\cdot ARA(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})\nonumber \\
 & =-\frac{\mathrm{v}\cdot\mathrm{\mathit{U}^{\prime\prime}(\mathrm{v})}}{\mathrm{\mathit{U}^{\prime}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})}}.\label{eq:RRAFunction}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the relationship between ARA and RRA functions in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RRAFunction"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, it is clear that a constant relative risk aversion (CRRA) investor must
 exhibit decreasing ARA.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both ARA and RRA characterize utility functions locally, but it is their
 global behavior for all possible values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}$
\end_inset

 that makes them useful in practice.
 Empirical evidence suggests that most investors exhibit decreasing absolute
 risk aversion (i.e.
 they are more willing to risk a fixed amount of money as their wealth increases
), but Relative Risk Aversion is known to depend in a complex way on age,
 sex, and wealth, among other characteristics (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BellanteGreen2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HalekEisenhauer2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for good discussions of this important point).
 It is therefore common practice to simply assume that investors exhibit
 Constant Relative Risk Aversion (i.e.
 to assume that the fraction of their wealth that they are willing to risk
 is independent of its level).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Subsection*
Derivation of Relative Risk Aversion Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Whereas absolute risk aversion was defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $ARA={\rm v_{0}}-{\rm v_{c}}$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
relative risk aversion
\emph default
 is defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
RRA=\dfrac{{\rm v_{0}}-{\rm v_{c}}}{{\rm v}_{0}}\label{eq: RRA}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm v_{c}}$
\end_inset

is the certainty equivalent as before, and the above definition allows one
 to write:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U({\rm v_{c})={\it U({\rm v_{0}-v_{0}{\it RRA{\rm )}}}.}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Let 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm Z}$
\end_inset

 be a random payoff per unit of initial investment 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm v_{0}}$
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E({\rm Z})=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $var({\rm Z})=\sigma_{{\rm Z}}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the positive random payoff 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm V}={\rm v_{0}}{\rm Z}$
\end_inset

 is a fair game gamble.
 Assume the investor is indifferent on a utility basis between receiving
 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm v}_{c}={\rm v}_{0}-{\rm v}_{0}{\it RRA}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm V}={\rm v_{0}}{\rm Z}$
\end_inset

, in the sense that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{E}\left[U({\rm v_{0}}{\rm Z})\right]=U\left({\rm v_{0}(1-{\it RRA})}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $RRA$
\end_inset

 represents the fraction of the wealth an investor is willing to give up
 to avoid the risk of an investment fair game gamble.
 Alternatively it is the
\emph on
 risk
\emph default
 
\emph on
premium
\emph default
 as a fraction of the wealth the investor will pay to avoid the risk of
 the gamble.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
One can now proceed as in the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $ARR$
\end_inset

 by equating the two term Taylor series of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[U({\rm v_{0}}{\rm Z})\right]$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=1$
\end_inset

 and the one term Taylor series of 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left({\rm v_{0}(1-{\it RRA})}\right)$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $RRA=0$
\end_inset

, solving the resulting equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $RRA$
\end_inset

, and ignoring a multiplicative factor.
 The result (left as an Exercise) is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
RRA({\rm v})=-{\rm v}\dfrac{U^{\prime\prime}(\mathrm{v})}{U^{\prime}({\rm v)}}.\label{eq: rraFnc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Marginal Utility and Risk Aversion of Common Utility Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We next explore the marginal utility, as well as the absolute and relative
 risk aversions, of some common utility functions.
 As risk aversion is rooted both in human psychology and in our environment
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Investors often become more risk seeking in good times (such as the run
 up to the Internet bubble in the late 1990s) and more risk averse in bad
 times (such as the period immediately following the start of the Great
 Financial Crisis in 2008).
\end_layout

\end_inset

, it is not easy to divine the true shape of an investor's utility function
 or degree of risk aversion.
 It has therefore become common practice to focus attention on utility functions
 that are analytically tractable, or which correspond to easily visualized
 economic goals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Logarithmic (or Log) Utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For log utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathit{U}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})=\ln(\mathrm{v}),\ \mathrm{v}>0,\label{eq:LogUtility}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{U^{\prime}}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})=\nicefrac{1}{\mathrm{v}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{U^{\prime\prime}}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})=-\nicefrac{1}{\mathrm{v}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 for positive 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}$
\end_inset

, and from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: ARAfunction"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RRAFunction"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
ARA\left(\mathrm{v}\right) & =\frac{1}{\mathrm{v}},\label{eq:ARALogUtility}\\
RRA\left(\mathrm{v}\right) & =1.\label{eq:RRALogUtility}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The marginal utility of wealth, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{U^{\prime}}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{1}{\mathrm{v}}$
\end_inset

, just as Daniel Bernoulli posited.
 Logarithmic utility plays an important role in finance, as it is closely
 related to the geometric mean, and we explore the link between the two
 in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:MakingUtiliyTheoryPractical"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Generalized Logarithmic (or GLUM) Utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generalized logarithmic utility is an exceptionally powerful and underappreciate
d variant of log utility.
 It was introduced in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Rubinstein1976"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Rubinstein1977"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as a flexible alternative to the CAPM, but did not achieve widespread popularit
y.
 It allows for a wide range of investor preferences, and lends itself naturally
 to the management of assets and liabilities, as both are easily interpreted
 as terms in the utility function.
 Formally
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathit{U}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})=\ln(\mathrm{v}+A),\ \mathrm{v}>-A,\label{eq:GLUMUtility}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{U^{\prime}}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})=\nicefrac{1}{\left(\mathit{\mathrm{v}}+A\right)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{U^{\prime\prime}}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})=-\nicefrac{1}{\left(\mathit{\mathrm{v}}+A\right)^{2}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}>-A$
\end_inset

, and from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: ARAfunction"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RRAFunction"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
ARA\left(\mathrm{v}\right) & =\frac{1}{\mathrm{v}+A},\label{eq:ARAGLUMUtility}\\
RRA\left(\mathrm{v}\right) & =\frac{\mathrm{v}}{\mathrm{v}+A}.\label{eq:RRAGLUMUtility}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The marginal utility of wealth, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{U^{\prime}}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})$
\end_inset

, is clearly decreasing in wealth, as is Absolute Risk Aversion.
 More importantly, Relative Risk Aversion is increasing, constant, or decreasing
 in wealth according to whether 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is positive, zero, or negative, allowing a wide range of investor preferences
 to be parsimoniously modeled.
 If we interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $-A$
\end_inset

 as the present value of the investor's liabilities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}+A$
\end_inset

 is her 
\emph on
actuarial surplus
\emph default
, or 
\emph on
discretionary wealth
\emph default
: she could, in principle at least, lose all of it, and still be able to
 meet her spending commitments.
 This is equivalent to the requirement that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}+A>0$
\end_inset

.The Generalized Logarithmic Utility function is therefore of great importance
 when modeling the wealth of households, and of insurers, who have large
 portfolios of assets that are offset by similar large portfolios of liabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generalized logarithmic utility is sometimes expressed in terms of returns
 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathit{U}(r)=\frac{\ln(1+\lambda\,r)}{\lambda},\ r>-\frac{1}{\lambda},\ \lambda>0,\label{eq:GLUMreturn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and expanding 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GLUMreturn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 in a two-term Taylor series around 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

 gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(r)\approx r\,-\,\frac{\lambda}{2}r^{2}.\label{eq:GLUMexpansion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Taking expecations on both sides of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GLUMreturn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\left[U(r)\right] & \approx E\left[r\right]\,-\,\frac{\lambda}{2}\left(\sigma^{2}\,+\,E\left[r\right]^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & \approx E\left[r\right]\,-\,\frac{\lambda}{2}\,\sigma^{2}\label{eq:GLUMexpansion2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which closely mimics the form of the Quadratic Utility function described
 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
MVOSection
\end_layout

\end_inset

, allowing us to identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 as a measure of risk aversion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "WilcoxZieffSatchell2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 use 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GLUMreturn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GLUMexpansion2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to allow the identification of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 by asking an investor a single question: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What is 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{max}$
\end_inset

, the largest fraction of your 
\emph on
financial
\emph default
 wealth you can lose without it ruining your life?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Viewed through the lens of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GLUMreturn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, this is equivalent to identifying the most negative return 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{max}=-f_{max}$
\end_inset

 that the investor can tolerate; at this return, her financial wealth is
 reduced to 0 and her utility becomes infinitely negative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "WilcoxZieffSatchell2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argue that it proves effective in practice to set 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\nicefrac{1}{f_{max}}$
\end_inset

.
 If the investor can lose all her financial wealth, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

, and she will invest log-optimally.
 Many investors say that they can lose between one-quarter and one-half
 of their financial wealth, corresponding to values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 between 2 and 4, which corresponds remarkably well to the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 obtained through the use of more complex and comprehensive questionnaires.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Power Utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A power utility function has the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathsf{\mathit{U}}(v;\,\gamma)}=\dfrac{\mathrm{v}^{1-\gamma}}{1-\gamma},\quad\mathrm{v}>0,\quad\gamma>0,\quad\gamma\neq1\label{eq:PowerUtility}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is an easy exercise to show that power utility has the risk aversion
 functions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
ARA\left(\mathrm{v}\right) & =\frac{\gamma}{\mathit{\mathrm{\mathrm{v}}}},\label{eq:ARAPowerUtility}\\
RRA\left(\mathrm{v}\right) & =\gamma.\label{eq:RRAPowerUtility}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and marginal utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathit{U^{\prime}}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})=\mathrm{v}^{-\gamma}.\label{eq:MarginalPowerUtility}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\longrightarrow1$
\end_inset

, power utility converges to logarithmic utility, and this is easily seen
 by applying L'Hospital's rule to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PowerUtility"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Investors who are attracted to the CRRA and long run growth properties
 of logarithmic utility, but who find it too risky for their taste, will
 find that power utility offers much of what logarithmic utility does, but
 with the ability to control risk by making an appropriate choice for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Exponential Utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exponential utility function has the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(\mathrm{v})=\frac{1-\mathrm{exp}(-c\cdot\mathrm{v})}{c},\,c>0,\mathrm{v}\geqslant0,\label{eq:ExponentialUtility}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 being a constant, so that its marginal utility is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{exp}(-c\cdot\mathrm{v})$
\end_inset

, and its risk aversion functions are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
ARA\left(\mathrm{v}\right) & =c\label{eq:ARAExponentialUtility}\\
RRA\left(\mathrm{v}\right) & =c\mathrm{v}.\label{eq:RRAExponentialUtility}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even though these do not correspond to commonly accepted views on investor
 risk aversions, exponential utility is sometimes used in economics on account
 of its analytic tractability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Quadratic Utility Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A quadratic utility function has the form 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{\mathit{U}(\mathit{\mathrm{v}})}= & \mathit{\mathrm{\mathrm{v}}}-\mathrm{\mathit{c}\,\mathit{\mathrm{v}}^{2},\,\mathit{c}>0,\mathit{\mathrm{v}}>0},\label{eq:QuadraticUtility}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 being a constant, so that its marginal utility is 
\begin_inset Formula $1-2\,c\,\mathrm{v}$
\end_inset

, and its risk aversion functions are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
ARA\left(\mathrm{v}\right) & =\frac{2\,c}{1-2\,c\,\mathit{\mathrm{\mathrm{v}}}}\label{eq:ARAQuadraticUtility}\\
RRA\left(\mathrm{v}\right) & =\frac{2\,c\,\mathit{\mathrm{\mathrm{v}}}}{1-2\,c\,\mathit{\mathrm{\mathrm{v}}}}.\label{eq:RRAQuadraticUtility}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But these risk aversion functions are infinite for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{\mathrm{\mathrm{v}}}=1/2\,b$
\end_inset

 and negative for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{\mathrm{\mathrm{v}}}>1/2\,b$
\end_inset

, and the quadratic utility function is therefore useless for such values
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{\mathrm{\mathrm{v}}}$
\end_inset

.
 In spite of these severe limitations, quadratic utility plays an important
 role in portfolio management because most any utility function can be approxima
ted reasonably well by a two-term Taylor series expansion around the current
 level of wealth.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All these five utility functions belong to the class of 
\bar under
H
\bar default
yperbolic 
\bar under
A
\bar default
bsolute 
\bar under
R
\bar default
isk 
\bar under
A
\bar default
version (HARA) utility functions, which are characterized by the fact that
 their reciprocals are linear functions of wealth, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
ARA\left(\mathrm{v}\right)=\frac{1}{\gamma\,\mathrm{v}\,+\,\delta}.\label{eq:HARAUtility}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
HARA utility functions are often used on account of their analytic tractability,
 even when a careful analysis of their properties suggests caution with
 their use.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:UtilityRiskAversion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 displays the risk aversion properties of these five utility functions,
 where these properties for quadratic utility only hold for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}<\nicefrac{1}{2c}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our view, the first three utility functions best model rational human
 economic behavior, while quadratic utility is a local approximation that
 works surprisingly well in practice for a variety of problems in portfolio
 management, even though it was characterized by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Arrow1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

absurd".
 As for exponential utility, it is egregious in failing to reflect typical
 investor behavior with respect to both ARA and RRA, but it sometimes used
 to justify mean–variance analysis for normally distributed security returns.
