\begin_layout Section
Expected Utility Maximization and Mean Variance Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
EUM with Certain Families of Returns Distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If asset returns are multivariate normal, then portfolio return 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{P}={\bf w^{\mathrm{\prime}}r}$
\end_inset

 has a normal distribution with a mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}={\bf w^{\prime}\boldsymbol{\mu}}$
\end_inset

 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{P}^{2}={\bf w^{\prime}}\boldsymbol{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}{\bf w}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case the expected utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[U\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}\cdot(1+r_{P})\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 will be a deterministic function 
\begin_inset Formula $g($
\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P},\,\sigma_{P})$
\end_inset

 of the portfolio's mean return and standard deviation.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing, it can be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\mu_{P},\,\sigma_{P})$
\end_inset

 is increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}$
\end_inset

 and decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{P}$
\end_inset

, and the EUM investor holds MinVar portfolios
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
The necessary details are provided in Chapter 4 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Ingersoll1987"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the sake of having a mathematical example where EUM does lead directly
 to mean-variance optimization, some quantitative finance papers and books
 discuss the fact that if an exponential utility function is used, and portfolio
 returns are normally distributed, then EUM leads to the quadratic utility
 form of MVO.
 But in this case, we have not only the weakness of the normal portfolio
 returns assumption, but also the inappropriateness of the exponential utility
 function due to its constant ARA and increasing RRA.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BenvenisteKolmRitter2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provide a more robust defence of mean-variance optimization for a class
 of 
\emph on
standard utility functions
\emph default
 that are increasing, strictly concave and continuously differentiable.
 They prove that utility maximization for any standard utility function
 is equivalent to mean-variance optimization for some level of risk aversion
 if and only if the security returns vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

 admits the representation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{r}=\bumu\,Z+\bueps,\label{eq:rRepresenation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bumu$
\end_inset

 is a vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is a scalar random variable with 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left[Z\right]=1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bueps$
\end_inset

 is a random vector with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E\left[\bueps^{\prime}\,\busigma^{-1}\,\,\bumu\right] & =0\label{eq:rRepresentation_1}\\
E\left[\bueps\,|\,Z\right] & =\mathbf{0}\label{eq:rRepresentation_2}\\
\mathbf{C}_{\bueps} & =\busigma\,-\,var(Z)\,\bumu\,\bumu^{\prime}\label{eq:rRepresentation_3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for some Positive Semi-Definite covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\busigma=\mathbf{C}_{\mathbf{r}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An empirical justification for quadratic utility is provided by the frequently
 referenced study by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "LevyMarkowitz1979"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, who compared the performance of log utility with that of an approximation
 based on quadratic utility, using actual returns for 149 investment companies
 from 1958 to 1967.
 While their conclusions indicate that quadratic utility provides a reasonable
 approximation to log utility, the results are based on a limited data set
 and must be applied with care to modern markets in which a wide range of
 derivatives are traded.
 Consequently, their results, while useful, do not provide convincing evidence
 for the adequacy of the quadratic utility approximation to expected log
 utility in the context of modern financial markets.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KrollLevyMarkowitz1984"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 expands on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Levy1979"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 – it considers a wide range of utility functions, and also explores the
 use of individual securities in place of funds, but, like its predecessor,
 does not explore the use of options or other derivatives.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
Additionally, security returns do not follow a multivariate normal distribution:
 there is considerable empirical evidence that such an assumption is not
 justified for the majority of assets.
 For example, the returns of small-cap stocks and hedge fund returns are
 often highly non-normal, exhibiting both skewness and kurtosis.
 Elliptical distributions are somewhat more promising, but their elliptical
 contours of constant probability also often fail to adequately capture
 the reality of multivariate returns distributions that occur in practice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Last, but not least, one should keep in mind that since arithmetic returns
 are bounded below by 
\begin_inset Formula $-100\%$
\end_inset

, no standard distribution (e.g.
 normal distribution, t– or skew–t distribution) that assigns positive probabili
ty to all intervals will be entirely adequate.
 One way in which to address this problem is to use log–normal returns,
 which are bounded below by 
\begin_inset Formula $-100\%$
\end_inset

 and which compound correctly over time, but which do not aggregate to a
 log–normal distribution when weighted and aggregated across portfolio assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Expected Utility Taylor Series Approximation and Quadratic Utility 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A common alternative approach to assuming portfolio normal returns is to
 assume that the investor uses a constant relative risk aversion (CRRA)
 utility function, and use a two-term plus remainder Taylor series expansion
 of the utility function to show that EUM leads to MVO portfolios.
 In doing so, one needs to decide what value to do the Taylor series expansion
 about, and the two natural choices are either to expand expected utility
 about portfolio mean return 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}$
\end_inset

 or expand it about 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{P}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Using the latter choice gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(\mathrm{v}_{0}\cdot(1+\mathit{r_{P}}))=U(\mathrm{v}_{0})+U^{\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})\cdot r_{P}+\dfrac{1}{2}U^{\prime\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0}\cdot(1+\mathit{\mu_{P}}))\cdot r_{P}^{2}+HOT\label{eq: utilityTaylorSeries}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where the higher-order terms 
\begin_inset Formula $HOT$
\end_inset

 depend on the higher order moments of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{P}$
\end_inset

.
 Taking expectations gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{E}\left[U(\mathrm{v}_{0}\cdot(1+\mathit{r_{P}}))\right] & =U(\mathrm{v}_{0})+U^{\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})\cdot\mathrm{E}\left[r_{P}\right]+\dfrac{1}{2}U^{\prime\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})\cdot\mathrm{E}\left[r_{P}^{2}\right]+\mathrm{E}\left(HOT\right)\nonumber \\
 & =U(\mathrm{v}_{0})+U^{\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})\cdot\mu_{P}+\dfrac{1}{2}U^{\prime\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})\cdot\left(\sigma_{P}^{2}+\mu_{P}^{2}\right)+\mathrm{E}\left(HOT\right)\label{eq: expectedUtilityTaylorWithHOT}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ignoring the expected value of the higher order terms, and recalling that
 the argument of the utility function on the left hand side is the end of
 period portfolio value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

, we have the approximation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{E}\left[U(\mathrm{V})\right] & \thickapprox U(\mathrm{v}_{0})\,+\,U^{\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})\,\left(\mu_{P}\,+\,\dfrac{1}{2}\cdot\dfrac{U^{\prime\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})}{U^{\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})}\cdot\left(\sigma_{P}^{2}\,+\,\mu_{P}^{2}\right)\right)\nonumber \\
 & =U(\mathrm{v}_{0})\,+\,U^{\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})\,\left(\mu_{P}\,-\,\dfrac{1}{2}\,ARA_{U}(\mathrm{v}_{0})\cdot\left(\sigma_{P}^{2}\,+\,\mu_{P}^{2}\right)\right)\label{eq: equivalentExpectedUtilityAroundZeroApprox}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $ARA_{U}(\mathrm{v}_{0})$
\end_inset

 is the absolute risk aversion function for the utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
So long as 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{\prime}(\mathrm{v}_{0})$
\end_inset

 is positive, which will be the case for any strictly increasing utility
 function, maximizing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[U(\mathrm{V})\right]$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to maximizing the mean-variance objective function with a
 special value of the risk aversion parameter that is determined by the
 utility function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{U}(\mu_{P},\,\sigma_{P})=\mu_{P}-\dfrac{1}{2}ARA_{U}(\mathrm{v}_{0})\cdot\left(\sigma_{P}^{2}+\mu_{P}^{2}\right).\label{eq: equivalentxpectedUtilityTwoTermTaylor}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Note that the above mean-variance objective function coincides with the
 quadratic utility functions of Section 2.3 only if, in addition to replacing
 
\begin_inset Formula $ARA(\mathrm{v}_{0})$
\end_inset

 above by the general risk aversion parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, one assumes (as is often the case) that the portfolio mean return is so
 small relative to the portfolio standard deviation that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}^{2}$
\end_inset

 can be dropped in the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{U}(\mu_{P},\,\sigma_{P})$
\end_inset

.
 In this case we are back to the quadratic utility version of MVO discussed
 extensively in that section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
However, the dropping of the expected values of the higher order terms in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: utilityTaylorSeries"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is in general questionable in view of the empirical evidence that asset
 returns are non–normally distributed, and often exhibit skewness and fat
 tails to a greater or lesser degree, particularly in the case of small-cap
 and micro-cap stocks, and in hedge fund returns.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we mention that the Taylor series expansion of a utility function
 about a portfolio mean return 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}$
\end_inset

 results in an expression that depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{P}$
\end_inset

 differently than 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: equivalentExpectedUtilityAroundZeroApprox"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, but which in general depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}$
\end_inset

 in a utility function dependent manner.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Expected Quadratic Utility and QP Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that direct use of a quadratic utility function of wealth, expressed
 via portfolio return gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{E}\left[U_{quadratic}(\mathrm{V})\right]= & \mathrm{E}\left[\mathrm{v}_{0}\,(1\,+\,\mbox{r_{P}})\,-\,b\,\mathrm{v}_{0}^{2}\,(1\,+\,\mathit{r_{P}})^{2}\right]\nonumber \\
= & \mathrm{v}_{0}\,\mathrm{E}\left[1\,+\,\mbox{r_{P}}\,-\,b\cdot\mathrm{v}_{0}\,(1\,+\,2\mathit{r_{P}}\,+\,r_{P}^{2})\right]\nonumber \\
= & \mathrm{v}_{0}\,(1\,-\,\mathrm{v}_{0}\,b)\,+\,(1\,-\,2\,b\,\mathrm{v}_{0})\,\mathrm{E}\left[r_{P}\right]\,-\,b\,\mathrm{v}_{0}\,\mathrm{E}\left[r_{P}^{2}\right]\nonumber \\
= & \mathrm{v}_{0}\,(1\,-\,\mathrm{v}_{0}\,b)\,+\,(1\,-\,2\,b\,\mathrm{v}_{0})\,\left[\mu_{P}\,-\,\dfrac{b\,\mathrm{v}_{0}}{1-2\,b\,\mathrm{v}_{0}}\,(\sigma_{P}^{2}\,+\,\mu_{P}^{2})\right].\label{eq: expectedQuadraticUtility}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}_{0}<2b$
\end_inset

, maximization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[U(\mathrm{V})\right]$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to maximization of the quantity in the square bracket above,
 which is not surprisingly a special case of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: equivalentExpectedUtilityAroundZeroApprox"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 being the quadratic utility function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
\noindent
Expected Quadratic Utility QP Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Re-writing 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: equivalentxpectedUtilityTwoTermTaylor"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with the ARA factor replaced by a general risk aversion parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{Q}_{U}(\mu_{P},\,\sigma_{P}) & =\mu_{P}-\dfrac{1}{2}\lambda\left(\sigma_{P}^{2}+\mu_{P}^{2}\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}={\bf w'\boldsymbol{\mu}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{P}^{2}={\bf w'}\mathbf{C}{\bf w},$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 being the returns covariance matrix, is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{\mathrm{Q}_{\mathit{U}}(\mu_{\mathit{P}},\,\sigma_{\mathit{P}})} & ={\bf w^{\prime}\boldsymbol{\mu}}-\lambda\cdot(\mathbf{w}^{\prime}\mathbf{C}{\bf w+w^{\prime}\boldsymbol{\mu\mu}'{\bf w)}}\\
 & ={\bf w^{\prime}\boldsymbol{\mu}}-\lambda\cdot w^{\prime}\check{\mathbf{C}}\mathbf{w}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{\mathbf{C}}=\mathbf{C}+\bumu\bumu^{\prime}=E\left[\mathbf{r}\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
In other words, the use of a quadratic utility function in the EUM framework
 leads to an objective function that differs from the standard QU objective
 function only by virtue of replacing the covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 in the latter with the second moment matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{\mathbf{C}}=\mathrm{E}\left[\mathbf{r}\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Keeping in mind the fact that many practitioners estimate the returns covarianc
e by assuming zero mean for the returns, this is perhaps not a significant
 difference between maximizing the expected value of quadratic utility and
 use of the QU optimization form of MVO.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Objections to Utility Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In spite of its impeccable pedigree, EUM has long been plagued by paradoxes
 and inconsistent choices made by participants in controlled laboratory
 experiments.
 These experiments are most often expressed in the form of choices between
 lotteries that look superficially different, but which, upon reflection,
 prove to be similar.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Alchian1953"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 offers the following example, which he attributes to Markowitz.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A friend offers you the choice of participation in one of three lotteries:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Lottery A consists of 2,000 tickets, two of which are marked $1,000 and
 the rest are marked $0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Lottery B consists of 2,000 tickets, twenty of which are marked $100 and
 the rest are marked $0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Lottery C consists of 2,000 tickets, one of which is marked $1,000, ten
 of which are marked $100, and the rest are marked $0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How would you rank these lotteries, and why? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A simple calculation shows that lottery C can be synthesized by flipping
 a fair coin that forces participation in lottery A or lottery B, each with
 a probability of 50%.
 Under the VNM axioms, it cannot therefore be rationally preferred to both
 lotteries A and B.
 In practice, however, a surprising number of people who are presented with
 this choice rank lottery C either first or third among these three lotteries!
 It is an easy matter to determine that the expected payoff from each of
 these lotteries is $1, so that the error is not driven by their expected
 payoffs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chapter 15 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Levy2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 documents a variety of similar paradoxes due to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Allais1953"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Ellsberg1961"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and others, in which volunteers systematically make choices that violate
 the EUM paradigm.
 Many, but not all, of these paradoxes are driven by the presence of rare
 outcomes which prove disproportionately attractive or repellent to participants
, or by a presentation that disguises the common aspects of seemingly different
 choices; but some, such as Ellsberg's paradox, are also driven by a human
 aversion to ambiguity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ellsberg's paradox can be illustrated by a simple coin tossing game in which
 the coin that is tossed can be chosen by the participant.
 The first coin that is offered to the participant is known to be fair,
 i.e
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{Head,\,1}=p_{Tail,\,1}=\frac{1}{2}.\label{eq:FairCoin1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second coin is known to be fair in expectation – the probability that
 it comes up heads not known to the participant, who knows only that it
 is uniformly distributed on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 It is easily seen that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{E}\left[p_{Head,\,2}\right]=\mathrm{E}\left[p_{Tail,\,2}\right]=\frac{1}{2}.\label{eq:FairCoin2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regardless of which coin she chooses, she wins $1 if the coin comes up heads,
 and loses $1 if it comes up tails.
 The expected value of both games is 0, and their expected utilities are
 identical for any level of initial wealth, and for any well–defined utility
 function, but individuals who are offered this choice overwhelmingly choose
 the first coin, and exhibit a deep aversion to the uncertainty associated
 with the second coin.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No perfect resolution to these paradoxes exist, as they appear to be deeply
 rooted in the way the human mind works
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KahnemanTversky2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 offers a comprehensive and readable account of many of these paradoxes
 and their relationship to the way in which our minds work (or are currently
 thought to work).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In early work, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Markowitz1952b"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 suggests that utility would be determined by a change in, rather than the
 absolute level of, an investor's wealth, and it is worth re–examining the
 St.
 Petersburg Paradox in this light.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an investor with initial wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

, and logarithmic utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(\mathrm{v}\right)=\ln\left(\mathrm{v}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The change in her expected utility from playing the St.
 Petersburg game without paying any entrance fee is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Delta U_{Free}\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}\right) & =\mathrm{E}\left[U\left(\mathrm{V}\right)\right]\,-\,U\left(\mathrm{v_{0}}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{k\,\geqslant\,1}\frac{1}{2^{k}}\cdot\ln\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}+2^{k}\right)\,-\,U\left(\mathrm{v_{0}}\right).\label{eq:DeltaUStPetersburgFree}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If, on the other hand, she must pay a fixed amount, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\$P\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

, for the privilege of playing the game, the change in her expected utility
 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Delta U_{Paid}\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}\right) & =\mathrm{E}\left[U\left(\mathrm{V}\right)\right]\,-\,U\left(\mathrm{v_{0}}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{k\,\geqslant\,1}\frac{1}{2^{k}}\cdot\ln\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}+2^{k}-P\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}\right)\right)\,-\,U\left(\mathrm{v_{0}}\right),\label{eq:DeltaUStPetersburgPriced}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and we can use search techniques to determine the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 that forces 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta U_{Paid}\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 to equal 0 (i.e.
 for no change in utility) for any value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:StPetersburgRevisited"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 displays 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\,\Delta U_{Free}\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\,P\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{P\left(\mathrm{v}_{0}\right)}{\mathrm{v}_{0}}$
\end_inset

 for values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

 ranging from $1 to $8,192.
 
\end_layout

