\begin_layout Standard
As wealth increases, the incremental utility gained by participation in
 the game becomes vanishingly small, and the maximum price that an investor
 would pay for the privilege of participation grows slowly (approximately
 logarithmically) with wealth.
 Strikingly, a participant with a wealth of $4 would be willing to risk
 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 her wealth on the St.
 Petersburg game, while one with a wealth of $1 would actually borrow $1.816
 and pay $2.816 for the privilege of participating! At the other extreme,
 an investor with $8,192 would pay only $13.95 to participate in this game.
 The results in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:StPetersburgRevisited"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 accord reasonably well with the results of experiments conducted with actual
 subjects with varying degrees of wealth.
 Also of interest is the fact that the additional utility gained by participatin
g in the St.
 Petersburg game converges to the fraction of her wealth that she would
 pay for the privilege of participating.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Markowitz's insight that utility should be driven by changes in wealth,
 and not by the level of wealth, is the starting point for a variety of
 proposed resolutions to these paradoxes.
 
\emph on
Prospect Theory
\emph default
, introduced in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KahnemanTversky1979"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, proposes that at any level of wealth, investors will evaluate lotteries
 through the lens of a sharply kinked and S–shaped 
\emph on
Value function
\emph default
 that is gently increasing (and concave) in gains and sharply decreasing
 (and convex) in losses, both measured from the current level of wealth.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HanSuiYang2026"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that investors appear to apply Prospect Theory in their evaluation
 of mutual funds for investment, and in rough accordance with the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "TverskyKahneman1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 value function applied to each fund's past returns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Almost contemporaneously, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "LoomesSudgen1982"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proposed 
\emph on
Regret Theory
\emph default
, which constructs a modified utility function that captures the regret
 or joy that an investor might feel on account of both the choices they
 make and the results they achieve.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BleichrodtWakker2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provide an excellent retrospective on Regret Theory and compare the insights
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "LoomesSudgen1982"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to those in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KahnemanTversky1979"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "LevyKroll1976"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Levy2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 propose stochastic dominance as the appropriate lens through which to compare
 investments, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "TverskyKahneman1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 present an updated version of their theory, now called 
\emph on
Cumulative Prospect Theory
\emph default
, to better accommodates multiple outcomes and also to correct some of its
 failures that relate to stochastic dominance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While these approaches have all attracted significant attention, and almost
 universally argue that the VNM axioms are an overly restrictive definition
 of rational behavior, they have not had a significant practical impact
 on portfolio construction for a variety of reasons, including:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Most investors cannot specify their personal utility function with any degree
 of precision,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
These theories tend to focus on lotteries with a few discrete outcomes,
 while security returns are a continuous random variable,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The joint distribution of security returns is not stable – it exhibits significa
nt time variation, and is not easily modeled, complicating the computation
 of expected utility, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The distribution of a portfolio's returns must be obtained from that of
 its constituents by evaluating a high–order convolution integral over the
 joint distribution of individual security returns, again complicating the
 computation of expected utility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, in spite of its enormous clarifying impact on the the underpinnings
 of portfolio theory, utility theory has not transformed the practice of
 portfolio management, and, in the next section, we discuss how some of
 its insights can be used in practice to good effect.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Making Utility Theory Practical
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:MakingUtiliyTheoryPractical"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The biggest single stumbling block to the use of utility theory in portfolio
 construction is the almost universal inability to specify one's utility
 function.
 We therefore suggest focusing on a few utility functions that translate
 naturally to reasonable economic objectives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We recommend thinking about utility functions in terms of their Relative
 Risk Aversion, and not their Absolute Risk Aversion, because most investors
 think naturally in terms of return and risk, and not in terms of lotteries.
 Given that the expected returns of most asset classes are not large, an
 investor's wealth will not vary significantly from one period to the next,
 and it seems to us that it most natural to focus on utility functions with
 Constant Relative Risk Aversion, particularly logarithmic and power utility.
 When one wishes to model assets as well as liabilities, Generalized Logarithmic
 utility is almost always the best choice, as the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as the negative of the present value of one's liabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a rich literature (and a correspondingly angry debate) on log utility
 and log–optimal investment, as maximizing log utility is equivalent to
 maximizing geometric return, and thus to maximizing terminal wealth.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "MacleanThorpZiemba2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provide a concise introduction to the theory and practice of log–optimal
 investment, as well as useful guide to the controversies that surround
 it.
 To expose the central idea, we let 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},\,r_{2},\,\cdots,\,r_{T}$
\end_inset

 be the return of a portfolio with an initial value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{v}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The portfolio's terminal value, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{T}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{V}_{T} & =\mathrm{v}_{0}\cdot\prod_{i\,=\,1}^{T}\left(1+r_{i}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\mathrm{v}_{0}\cdot\left(1+g\right)^{T}\label{eq:GeometricReturn1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, the geometric return, is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g=\left(\prod_{i\,=\,1}^{T}\left(1+r_{i}\right)\right)^{\frac{1}{T}}-1.\label{eq:GeometricReturn2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also write 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GeometricReturn1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{V}_{T} & =\mathrm{v}_{0}\cdot\exp\left(\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{T}\ln\left(1+r_{i}\right)\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\mathrm{v}_{0}\cdot\exp\left(\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{T}\widetilde{r}_{i}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\mathrm{v}_{0}\cdot\exp\left(T\cdot\frac{1}{T}\sum_{i=1}^{T}\widetilde{r}_{i}\right)\nonumber \\
 & \longrightarrow\mathrm{v}_{0}\cdot\exp\left(T\cdot\mathrm{E}\left[\widetilde{r}\right]\right),\label{eq:LogUtility1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the last step rests on the assumption that the distribution of returns
 is stable over time.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{x}$
\end_inset

 is monotonically increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, it is clear that maximizing terminal wealth is equivalent to maximizing
 expected logarithmic return, or equivalently, to maximizing expected log
 utility for the portfolio.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
AssetReturnsChapter
\end_layout

\end_inset

, it is shown that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g\thickapprox\mu_{r}\,-\,\frac{1}{2}\,\sigma_{r}^{2},\label{eq:LogUtility2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so that maximizing 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is approximately equivalent to a mean–variance optimization with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If this level of relative risk aversion seems too low, we can explore power
 utility functions with higher levels of risk aversion, and experiments
 have shown that RRA lies between 2 and 4 for a large fraction of the population.
 Having chosen a utility function, we proceed in one of two ways:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set the parameters of the chosen utility function to match the investor's
 RRA (this is often determined via a questionnaire or by analyzing her choices
 in one or more lotteries), and construct mean–variance optimal portfolios
 with the same level of risk aversion.
 In effect, we construct a local approximation to our preferred utility
 function, allowing the entire machinery of mean–variance analysis to be
 brought to bear on the problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Insert the chosen utility function into a simulation and historical back–testing
 engine, and then identify the utility maximizing optimal portfolio using
 sampling or some form or gradient search.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "AdlerKritzman2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Sharpe2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describe simple approaches to utility maximization in an asset–only setting,
 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Wilcox2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "WilcoxSatchell2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show how to optimize the growth of actual surplus using Generalized Logarithmic
 Utility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each method has its advantages, though satisfactory results can be obtained
 from either one when simple securities with relatively little skew or kurtosis
 are the only financial instruments used.
 When securities with skewed and fat–tailed distributions, such as small–cap
 stocks, high–yield bonds, options and other non–linear derivatives, are
 used, the second method dominates.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regardless of the method used, it is vital to start with good, forward–looking,
 estimates of expected returns of the various markets in which one can invest
 and to ensure that one's estimates of individual security returns and volatilit
ies are consistent with these estimates
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The expected return of an index is the market–value weighted average of
 the expected return of its constituents, and its volatility is given by
 a quadratic form that uses as inputs the market–value weights and the covarianc
e matrix of its constituents.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, as estimation errors can cause extreme instability in optimal portfolios,
 particularly at low levels of risk aversion, effectively nullifying any
 theoretical advantage of direct utility maximization.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ChopraZiemba1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that the estimation errors in expected returns have ten times the
 impact of estimation errors in variances, and twenty times the impact of
 estimation errors in covariances.
 
\end_layout

